faqs:
  - q: "How does the savings goal calculator work?"
    a: "Enter your target amount, current savings, monthly contribution, and expected interest rate. The calculator uses compound interest to estimate how many months it will take to reach your goal, along with total interest earned."
  - q: "What interest rate should I use?"
    a: "Use the current rate your savings account or investment pays. High-yield savings accounts typically pay higher rates than standard accounts. If you're unsure, try 0% to see the baseline with no interest, then add your rate to see the impact."
  - q: "Does the calculator account for compound interest?"
    a: "Yes. The calculator compounds interest monthly, which is standard for most savings accounts. This means interest earned each month is added to your balance and earns interest in subsequent months."
  - q: "What if I already have some savings?"
    a: "Enter your current savings in the Current Savings field. The calculator will factor in your existing balance and only calculate how long the remaining amount will take to accumulate."
  - q: "How can I reach my savings goal faster?"
    a: "Two levers: increase your monthly contribution or find a higher interest rate. Even a small increase in monthly savings compounds significantly over time. Use the calculator to model different scenarios."
  - q: "Is this calculator accurate for investments?"
    a: "The calculator assumes a fixed interest rate and regular monthly contributions. Real investment returns vary month to month. For investments, treat the result as an estimate — actual time may be shorter or longer depending on market performance."
